<node id="SODA-OPT">
  <data key="d0">SODA-OPT</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">SODA-OPT is a compiler tool designed to extend the MLIR infrastructure, enabling the generation of custom hardware accelerators. It serves as a framework for automatically generating high-quality hardware accelerators through high-level synthesis and optimizing applications for such accelerators. Specifically, SODA-OPT automates the process of outlining and optimizing computational kernels from high-level frameworks, including operations from the linalg, affine, or scf dialects. This optimization tool outlines and tiles kernel regions to enhance performance, making it particularly effective in various benchmarks compared to other high-level synthesis (HLS) tools. SODA-OPT is a comprehensive pipeline that not only optimizes applications but also addresses challenges in developing highly specialized systems by leveraging the capabilities of MLIR.&lt;SEP&gt;SODA-OPT is an MLIR abstraction and compiler transformation that performs automated host and device code partitioning of complete ML applications.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e4a8349a158e75492141b2c564253c34&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-26064d6a9f50906d6ea350494b2c8125&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-28dc18967653f15f5790c6607c1d02e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1dc4a868072141c957b2a260dbd14959&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-434fe16e9313a890ebca0145e7c4f4e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0a501c4c92dd83d3a8ada5a6a154e5be&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5f5f1607b7d6e9df741b1a30c64d74da&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8993318ac130965c4393ca23d77a9b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-72c65d5d8186bf9226fd5144f638e4f4</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322486</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="MLIR">
  <data key="d0">MLIR</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">MLIR, which stands for Machine Learning Intermediate Representation, is a flexible and extensible framework designed to support the development of compilers. It serves as an intermediate representation that enables the definition of new dialects and transformations for representing domain-specific languages. MLIR has been utilized in various projects such as SODA-OPT and the MLIR-based Compiler Flow project, where it facilitates hardware/software partitioning and optimization passes.

Specifically, MLIR is used by SODA-OPT to define information at multiple levels of abstraction, enabling high-level analysis and transformations. It also plays a crucial role in building reusable, extensible, and modular compiler infrastructures. Additionally, MLIR has been employed in the DRIPS framework for representing and optimizing computational graphs, as well as in the development of ML-CGRA (Machine Learning Computation Graph Reconfigurable Array), where it aids in easier integration of various passes.

Overall, MLIR is a versatile tool that supports the creation of advanced compiler infrastructures, making it an essential component in modern software and hardware optimization processes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e4a8349a158e75492141b2c564253c34&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-28dc18967653f15f5790c6607c1d02e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1dc4a868072141c957b2a260dbd14959&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-434fe16e9313a890ebca0145e7c4f4e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5f5f1607b7d6e9df741b1a30c64d74da&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-72c65d5d8186bf9226fd5144f638e4f4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-46c9950a6d7f273199820d455082eed4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-204207b9dedb6d8465abf466a8da7b22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7fde1c2f6a78bac431334c31848f80a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766410739</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
