<node id="MLIR Infrastructure">
  <data key="d0">MLIR Infrastructure</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">MLIR (Machine Learning Interchangeable Representation) infrastructure supports the development of ML-CGRA, an end-to-end compilation framework.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Coarse-Grained Reconfigurable Array (CGRA)">
  <data key="d0">Coarse-Grained Reconfigurable Array (CGRA)</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">CGRAs are hardware devices that can achieve higher energy efficiency while maintaining adaptability to different computational patterns, offering a flexible yet efficient alternative to general-purpose processors and accelerators.&lt;SEP&gt;CGRAs are hardware devices that can achieve higher energy efficiency while maintaining adaptability to different computational patterns.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="ONNX">
  <data key="d0">ONNX</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">ONNX (Open Neural Network Exchange) is a format used by various machine learning frameworks and is compatible with ML-CGRA.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="GitHub">
  <data key="d0">GitHub</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">GitHub is the platform where ML-CGRA's source code is available for download and contribution.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="General Purpose Processors (CPU/GPU)">
  <data key="d0">General Purpose Processors (CPU/GPU)</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">General-purpose processors like CPU and GPU are general computing devices that can be used to run applications but may not be as energy-efficient or flexible for specialized tasks compared to CGRAs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Application-Specific Integrated Circuit (ASIC)">
  <data key="d0">Application-Specific Integrated Circuit (ASIC)</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">ASICs are specialized hardware devices designed for specific applications and can be more efficient for certain tasks compared to CGRAs or general-purpose processors, though less flexible.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dataflow Graph (DFG)">
  <data key="d0">Dataflow Graph (DFG)</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Dataflow graph mapping is a technique used to map computations on CGRAs, focusing on inner-most loop kernel acceleration through low-level instruction-based compilation approaches.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Machine Learning Acceleration">
  <data key="d0">Machine Learning Acceleration</data>
  <data key="d1">category</data>
  <data key="d2">ML-CGRA aims to provide efficient machine learning acceleration on CGRAs through various optimization passes and integration with ML frameworks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Machine Learning Models">
  <data key="d0">Machine Learning Models</data>
  <data key="d1">category</data>
  <data key="d2">ML-CGRA is designed to efficiently map and accelerate various machine learning models on CGRAs, providing a flexible platform for model execution.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="High-Level ML Frameworks">
  <data key="d0">High-Level ML Frameworks</data>
  <data key="d1">category</data>
  <data key="d2">ML-CGRA leverages semantic information from high-level ML frameworks to improve mapping efficiency on CGRAs, providing a more robust solution compared to low-level instruction-based approaches.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Low-Level Instruction-Based Compiler Approaches">
  <data key="d0">Low-Level Instruction-Based Compiler Approaches</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Current solutions for CGRAs use low-level instruction-based compiler approaches that do not fully leverage semantic information from ML models, limiting their efficiency in mapping on reconfigurable substrates.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Semantic Information">
  <data key="d0">Semantic Information</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">ML-CGRA aims to utilize and leverage semantic information from ML models for efficient mapping on CGRAs, providing a more flexible and effective solution compared to traditional compiler approaches.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Machine Learning (ML) Applications">
  <data key="d0">Machine Learning (ML) Applications</data>
  <data key="d1">category</data>
  <data key="d2">A variety of machine learning applications are gaining prominence across multiple fields, finding fast solutions for challenging problems and driving the need for efficient hardware acceleration platforms.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322484</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Modern Deployments">
  <data key="d0">Modern Deployments</data>
  <data key="d1">category</data>
  <data key="d2">Modern deployments require rapid retargeting capabilities and efficient model evaluation to continuously improve performance in hardware-acceleration platforms, making CGRAs a valuable solution.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Performance Concerns">
  <data key="d0">Performance Concerns</data>
  <data key="d1">category</data>
  <data key="d2">ML-CGRA addresses performance concerns by facilitating cycle-level and RTL simulations through its CGRA runtime library, allowing users to evaluate detailed performance issues at a low level.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Compiler Optimizations">
  <data key="d0">Compiler Optimizations</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Design space exploration approaches that consider compiler optimizations can find high-performance implementation points but still operate at the instruction level, inheriting brittleness in CGRA user modifications.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Instruction Level">
  <data key="d0">Instruction Level</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Traditional compilation frameworks operate at the instruction level, which can be brittle for CGRA users who cannot easily modify generated code or repeat design space exploration processes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Cycle-Level Simulation">
  <data key="d0">Cycle-Level Simulation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The CGRA runtime library supports cycle-level simulations for evaluating detailed performance concerns, providing users with comprehensive insights into model behavior on CGRAs.&lt;SEP&gt;Cycle-level simulation is used to assess the performance of models at a detailed, fine-grained level.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-72c65d5d8186bf9226fd5144f638e4f4</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Register-Transfer Level (RTL) Simulation">
  <data key="d0">Register-Transfer Level (RTL) Simulation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The CGRA runtime library supports RTL simulations for evaluating low-level performance concerns, offering users insights into the behavior of models on the reconfigurable substrate.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="High-Level Structures in Code">
  <data key="d0">High-Level Structures in Code</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">ML-CGRA leverages high-level structures in code to improve overall performance, offering a more flexible and end-to-end solution compared to low-level instruction-based approaches.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Semantic Information Leverage">
  <data key="d0">Semantic Information Leverage</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Leveraging semantic information from ML models can significantly improve end-to-end performance by simplifying mapping on predefined parametric templates, offering a more efficient and flexible approach compared to traditional methods.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Conventional Compilation Flows">
  <data key="d0">Conventional Compilation Flows</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Traditional compilation flows require users to manually refine input models and inline specialized kernels, leading to reduced attractiveness of the CGRA substrate.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d3b54ca06794c60a35a49b96c496c299</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322485</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
