<node id="CGRA">
  <data key="d0">CGRA</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">CGRA stands for Configurable Gate Array (CGRA), which is a type of hardware architecture designed for flexible and efficient computation. CGRAs are reconfigurable architectures used to accelerate specific computational kernels, complex data processing pipelines, and parallel computing tasks. These architectures can be customized for various tasks and are particularly useful in accelerating SpMV kernels and machine learning models.

Coarse-Grained Reconfigurable Architecture (CGRA) is a hardware architecture that allows for runtime reconfiguration of the computational platform to run application kernels with different numbers of tiles and unrolling factors. It supports both parallel computing tasks and the acceleration of specific computational kernels, making it versatile in handling diverse computational requirements.

In summary, CGRA refers to Configurable Gate Array Reconfigurable Architecture, a hardware architecture that can be customized for various tasks and is used to accelerate complex data processing pipelines, SpMV kernels, and machine learning models. It supports runtime reconfiguration to optimize the execution of different application kernels.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-72c65d5d8186bf9226fd5144f638e4f4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e061de5d24e0a8bcadd81eaee61fe74&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-867038b972ebe25908221a61e9ba9a9c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ece4f507673e067d1b26b4c5db6aaef9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-57a3a682d8c8b22c568166b68710bb5e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b8e7ceb7ade808ddedfa769ab7b31be&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1db998302836079483ae0d5d650ee931&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-204207b9dedb6d8465abf466a8da7b22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-66bbd3d920ec2fc75c516befdf7597d1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7fde1c2f6a78bac431334c31848f80a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-072a87db7c5dbb5fd3ba6bae2d7254f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0663013f37b4f7c3740127aa091def5f</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766410730</data>
