<node id="Vector Tiles">
  <data key="d0">Vector Tiles</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Vector Tiles consist of fixed-point vector functional units for hybrid and fixed-point16 operations.&lt;SEP&gt;Vector tiles are utilized by applications requiring higher data parallelism in the VecPAC framework for achieving better performance.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-92e82cee01030c7760843fcd3f03ed32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fixed-Point32 Vector FUs">
  <data key="d0">Fixed-Point32 Vector FUs</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Fixed-Point32 Vector FUs are used in vector tiles for hybrid computation support.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fixed-Point16 Vector FUs">
  <data key="d0">Fixed-Point16 Vector FUs</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Fixed-Point16 Vector FUs are used in vector tiles for VecPAC architecture.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="VecPAC">
  <data key="d0">VecPAC</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">VecPAC is a vectorizable and precision-aware coarse-grained reconfigurable array (CGRA) design.&lt;SEP&gt;VecPAC is a hybrid CGRA design composed of tiles with scalar functional units and vector functional units that maximize performance across various applications.&lt;SEP&gt;VecPAC is a dynamic precision trading framework that supports multiple fixed-point16 lanes to maximize area efficiency.&lt;SEP&gt;VecPAC is a compiler toolchain that supports vectorized operations for different precision levels.&lt;SEP&gt;VecPAC is a compiler framework designed for vectorizing applications on CGRA architectures.&lt;SEP&gt;VecPAC is a hybrid CGRA design that includes both tiles with scalar FUs and tiles with vector FUs.&lt;SEP&gt;VecPAC is a design that performs vectorized memory accesses with varying degrees of success.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-867038b972ebe25908221a61e9ba9a9c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68c4558c96bf4490d4f7c6a8af629f49&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fb7fb6bd238c27a13ccbffd80022a059&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-709227a765c55f9d3440bf6ca2a72a60&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-92e82cee01030c7760843fcd3f03ed32&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Scalar Tile">
  <data key="d0">Scalar Tile</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">A Scalar Tile consists of floating-point 32-bit FUs and generates one output per cycle.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="CGRA (Coarse-Grained Reconfigurable Array)">
  <data key="d0">CGRA (Coarse-Grained Reconfigurable Array)</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">CGRA is a type of reconfigurable array used in VecPAC architecture for resource utilization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Vector Adder">
  <data key="d0">Vector Adder</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A Vector Adder supports 4-way vectorization with four lanes, each executing 16-bit fixed-point additions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fixed-Point64 Vector FUs">
  <data key="d0">Fixed-Point64 Vector FUs</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Fixed-Point64 Vector FUs are used to support fixed-point64 addition as a scalar adder.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-cda28e4ebe0ec435693bd0363dc0f134</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="LLVM Auto-Vectorization Pass">
  <data key="d0">LLVM Auto-Vectorization Pass</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The LLVM Auto-Vectorization pass is used to vectorize loops in code.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-867038b972ebe25908221a61e9ba9a9c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="MRRG">
  <data key="d0">MRRG</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">MRRG stands for Modulo Routing Resource Graph, which is used to map DFGs onto CGRA architectures.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-867038b972ebe25908221a61e9ba9a9c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DFG">
  <data key="d0">DFG</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Data Flow Graph (DFG) represents the data dependencies among operations in a program.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-867038b972ebe25908221a61e9ba9a9c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Loop Unrolling">
  <data key="d0">Loop Unrolling</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Loop unrolling is an optimization technique that increases the number of operations to improve performance by increasing ILP.&lt;SEP&gt;Loop unrolling is a transformation step in the MLIR dialect.&lt;SEP&gt;Loop unrolling is an optimization technique where the body of a loop is replicated several times, reducing the overhead and improving instruction-level parallelism.&lt;SEP&gt;Loop unrolling is a technique used in programming and hardware design to improve performance by reducing the number of iterations needed for loops.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-867038b972ebe25908221a61e9ba9a9c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b8e7ceb7ade808ddedfa769ab7b31be&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7fde1c2f6a78bac431334c31848f80a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6f7cad872120e96e22443543d20a47ae</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766410730</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dependent Memory Operations">
  <data key="d0">Dependent Memory Operations</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Dependent memory operations are those where the result of one operation depends on the value of another.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-867038b972ebe25908221a61e9ba9a9c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
