  <data key="d2">Steve Reinhardt is a contributor from Microsoft involved in the development of VecPAC.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-709227a765c55f9d3440bf6ca2a72a60</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Plasticine">
  <data key="d0">Plasticine</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Plasticine is a vector CGRA design composed of reconfigurable Pattern Compute Units (PCUs) and Pattern Memory Units (PMUs).</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-709227a765c55f9d3440bf6ca2a72a60</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fixed-Point Additions">
  <data key="d0">Fixed-Point Additions</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Fixed-point additions are arithmetic operations supported by the VecPAC framework in various bit-width configurations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-92e82cee01030c7760843fcd3f03ed32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="32-bit Fixed-Point Multiplication">
  <data key="d0">32-bit Fixed-Point Multiplication</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A 32-bit fixed-point multiplication is a type of arithmetic operation supported by the VecPAC framework, requiring multiple parallel 16-bit multiplications and appropriate shift operations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-92e82cee01030c7760843fcd3f03ed32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="16-bit Fixed-Point Multiplication">
  <data key="d0">16-bit Fixed-Point Multiplication</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">16-bit fixed-point multiplications are part of the vector multiplier support in the VecPAC framework for different precision arithmetic.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-92e82cee01030c7760843fcd3f03ed32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="64-bit Addition">
  <data key="d0">64-bit Addition</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A 64-bit addition is a type of arithmetic operation supported by the VecPAC framework, delivering carry-bit between appropriate sub-adders.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-92e82cee01030c7760843fcd3f03ed32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Loop Vectorization">
  <data key="d0">Loop Vectorization</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Loop vectorization transforms loop bodies to perform multiple scalar operations simultaneously on several vector elements.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-92e82cee01030c7760843fcd3f03ed32</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SPM">
  <data key="d0">SPM</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">SPM can perform memory operations.&lt;SEP&gt;SPM (Sparse Memory) refers to the memory constraints in streaming applications, which can significantly affect performance.&lt;SEP&gt;SPM stands for Scratchpad Memory, which is a component in the DRIPS architecture used for storing data.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b8e7ceb7ade808ddedfa769ab7b31be&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7fde1c2f6a78bac431334c31848f80a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766410730</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4×4 VecPAC Design">
  <data key="d0">4×4 VecPAC Design</data>
  <data key="d1">design</data>
  <data key="d2">The 4x4 VecPAC design supports different vectorization factors for 64-bit and 32-bit fixed-point operations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="LLVM Auto-Vectorization">
  <data key="d0">LLVM Auto-Vectorization</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">LLVM Auto-Vectorization is a technique that cannot be applied to kernels unable to be vectorized.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Kernel">
  <data key="d0">Kernel</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Kernels are components of the system that are memory-bound and thus affected by vectorization factors.&lt;SEP&gt;Kernels refer to individual components or functions within a larger system that perform specific tasks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-57a3a682d8c8b22c568166b68710bb5e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c70d15fac8cde95102112baf7572b83a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766410727</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Figure 9">
  <data key="d0">Figure 9</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Figure 9 illustrates the trade-off between accuracy and speedup across different application domains on VecPAC.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4×4 Scalar CGRA Baseline">
  <data key="d0">4×4 Scalar CGRA Baseline</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">The 4x4 scalar CGRA baseline is used as a reference for normalized performance comparisons.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="VecPAC Design">
  <data key="d0">VecPAC Design</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">The VecPAC design combines tiles with scalar FUs and vector FUs, aiming to optimize performance and accuracy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Vector Functional Units (VFUs)">
  <data key="d0">Vector Functional Units (VFUs)</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Vector functional units in VecPAC allow for lane fusion trading off parallelism for accuracy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1766322524</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Conventional Scalar CGRA">
  <data key="d0">Conventional Scalar CGRA</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Conventional scalar CGRAs are used as a benchmark to compare the performance of the VecPAC design.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0e2dc42cf9d2604980f8a4ea00b9e5e9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68c4558c96bf4490d4f7c6a8af629f49</data>
